== Ame no Hohi stuff ==
{{ill|Ame no Hohi|en}} is believed to be the ancestor of the Izumo no Omi.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Mason |first=Joseph Warren Teets |url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/The_Spirit_of_Shinto_Mythology/DCMvAAAAYAAJ?hl=en |title=The Spirit of Shinto Mythology |date=1939 |publisher=Fuzambo |language=en}}</ref>{{Page needed|date=September 2021}} As well as the priests of Izumo and the {{ill|Sugawara clan|en}}.<ref>{{Cite book |last1=Cali |first1=Joseph |url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/Shinto_Shrines/J1gEEAAAQBAJ?hl=en&gbpv=1&dq=Ame+no+Hohi+Izumo&pg=PA69&printsec=frontcover |title=Shinto Shrines: A Guide to the Sacred Sites of Japan's Ancient Religion |last2=Dougill |first2=John |date=2012-11-30 |publisher=University of Hawaii Press |isbn=978-0-8248-3775-4 |pages=69 |language=en}}</ref> {{ill|Nomi no Sukune|en}} is said to be the decedent of Amenohohi.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Sumo |url=https://www.worldhistory.org/Sumo/ |access-date=2021-09-04 |website=World History Encyclopedia |language=en}}</ref>
[[ja:建比良鳥命]]
He is the ancestor of the {{ill|Haji clan|en}}<ref>{{cite book |last1=Cali |first1=J. |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=J1gEEAAAQBAJ&pg=PA69 |title=Shinto Shrines: A Guide to the Sacred Sites of Japan's Ancient Religion |last2=Dougill |first2=J. |publisher=University of Hawaii Press |year=2012 |isbn=978-0-8248-3775-4 |page=69 |access-date=2020-11-21}}</ref>. and the [[Izumo clan]].<ref name=":1" />

== Names ==
Takehi-Nateru, also known by several other names such as Takehiratori no Mikoto, Takehinatori no Mikoto, and Ame no Hinatori.<ref name=":1" />

== Background ==
Takehi-Nateru is the child of {{ill|Ame no Hohi|en}}, one of the five male kami (divine beings) born from a special event known as the "trial by pledge" between two major deities, Amaterasu and Susanoo. {{ill|Ame no Hohi|en}} was sent to the {{nihongo|'''{{ill|Ashihara no Nakatsukuni|en}}'''|葦原の中つ国|{{trans.}} ''The middle country of [[reed bed]]s''}} to prepare for the [[Tenson korin]].<ref name=":1" />

== Role in Mythology ==
In the Kojiki, one of Japan's oldest records, Takehi-Nateru is mentioned as an ancestor to the [[Izumo clan|Izumo no Kuni no Miyatsuko]]. Both the Kojiki and Nihongi, another foundational text, narrate how {{ill|Ame no Hohi|en}} was tasked with preparing the {{nihongo|'''{{ill|Ashihara no Nakatsukuni|en}}'''|葦原の中つ国|{{trans.}} ''The middle country of [[reed bed]]s''}} but ultimately did not succeed in his mission.<ref name=":1" />

Despite this, Takehi-Nateru, played a crucial role alongside {{ill|Futsunushi|en}} in pacifying the {{ill|Ashihara no Nakatsukuni|en}}. They managed to subdue unruly deities and persuaded a prominent deity, [[Ōkuninushi|Ōnamuchi]], to leave the earthly realm. This accomplishment paved the way for the descent of the imperial grandchild, [[Ninigi-no-Mikoto|Ninigi]], and solidified the status of Takehi-Nateru and his father as forebears of the [[Izumo clan|Izumo no Kuni no Miyatsuko]], who served as advisors to the emperor.<ref name=":1" />

== Legacy ==
According to the Nihongi's account of [[Emperor Sujin]], Takehi-Nateru descended from heaven with divine treasures. These treasures were kept at [[Izumo-taisha]] and later handed over to the [[Emperor of Japan]]. However, this transfer led to conflicts among the Izumo, Furune, and Iiirine family branches, who were the keepers of these sacred items. Today, shrines in [[Izumo Province|Izumo]] and [[Inaba Province|Inaba]] honor Takehi-Nateru.<ref name=":1" />

