{{ill|Takehi-Nateru|ja|建比良鳥命|simple|User:Immanuelle/Takehi-Nateru|en:draft}} (建比良鳥命) is a Japanese god and son of {{ill|Ame no Hohi|en}},<ref name="web.archive.org-2023">{{Cite web|date=2023-03-21|title=Takehiratori {{!}} 國學院大學デジタルミュージアム|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230321165525/https://d-museum.kokugakuin.ac.jp/eos/detail/?id=9146|access-date=2024-03-24|website=web.archive.org}}</ref><ref name="web.archive.org-2023a">{{Cite web|date=2023-06-05|title=Amenohohi {{!}} 國學院大學デジタルミュージアム|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230605104153/https://d-museum.kokugakuin.ac.jp/eos/detail/?id=9434|access-date=2024-03-24|website=web.archive.org}}</ref><ref name="shintoshrines">{{Cite web|title=The Gods of Japan {{!}} Amaterasu-Ōkami 天照大御神 {{!}}Susanoo-no-Mikoto 須佐之男命|url=https://www.rodsshinto.com/amasusa|access-date=2024-03-24|website=shintoshrines|language=en}}</ref><ref name="More glimpses of unfamiliar Japan">{{Cite web|title=More glimpses of unfamiliar Japan|url=https://www.ojisanjake.com/2014/03/|access-date=2024-03-24|language=en}}</ref><ref name="英訳 出雲神話">{{Cite web|title=英訳 出雲神話/English Translation Izumo Myths::２．天の安の河の誓約-出雲神話翻訳研究会/The Man From Izumo tells the Izumo-myths of the Kojiki|url=http://izumo-kojiki.com/izumomyths/amaterasu/100/|access-date=2024-03-24|language=ja}}</ref> one of the five male kami (divine beings) born from a special event known as the "trial by pledge" between two major deities, Amaterasu and Susanoo. {{ill|Ame no Hohi|en}} was sent to the {{nihongo|'''{{ill|Ashihara no Nakatsukuni|en}}'''|葦原の中つ国|''The middle country of [[reed bed]]s''}} to prepare for the {{ill|Tenson korin|en}}.<ref name="web.archive.org-2023" />
He is the ancestor of many prominent families in, [[Izumo Province|Izumo]], [[Musashi Province|Musashi]], [[Chiba Prefecture|Chiba]], and [[Tsushima Province|Tsushima]].<ref name="shintoshrines" /><ref name="英訳 出雲神話" />
Ame no Hohi's other sons are {{ill|Ame-No-Wakahiko|en}} and {{ill|Ame-no-Hinadori|en}}.<ref name="Brown-1988">{{Cite book |last1=Brown |first1=Delmer M. |url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/The_Cambridge_History_of_Japan/A3_6lp8IOK8C?hl=en&gbpv=1&dq=Ame+no+Hohi&pg=PA346&printsec=frontcover |title=The Cambridge History of Japan |last2=Hall |first2=John Whitney |last3=Brown |first3=Delmer Myers |last4=Press |first4=Cambridge University |last5=Jansen |first5=Marius B. |last6=McCullough |first6=William H. |last7=Shively |first7=Donald H. |last8=Yamamura |first8=Kozo |last9=Duus |first9=Peter |date=1988 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-0-521-22352-2 |pages=346 |language=en}}</ref>
[[ja:建比良鳥命]] == Names == Takehi-Nateru, also known by several other names such as Takehiratori no Mikoto, Takehinatori no Mikoto, and Ame no Hinatori.<ref name="web.archive.org-2023" />
== Role in Mythology == In the Kojiki, the oldest Japanese book, Takehi-Nateru is mentioned as an ancestor to the [[Izumo clan|Izumo no Kuni no Miyatsuko]]. Both the [[Kojiki]] and [[Nihon Shoki]], narrate how {{ill|Ame no Hohi|en}} was tasked with preparing the {{nihongo|'''{{ill|Ashihara no Nakatsukuni|en}}'''|葦原の中つ国|''The middle country of [[reed bed]]s''}} but ultimately did not succeed in his mission.<ref name="web.archive.org-2023" />
So Takehi-Nateru and {{ill|Futsunushi|en}} went down to pacify {{ill|Ashihara no Nakatsukuni|en}}. They managed to subdue unruly deities and persuaded a prominent deity, [[Ōkuninushi|Ōnamuchi]], to leave the earthly realm. After their victory the heavenly grandchild [[Ninigi-no-Mikoto|Ninigi]] descended to the Earth and Takehi-Nateru became the ancestor of the [[Izumo clan|Izumo no Kuni no Miyatsuko]], who ruled [[Izumo Province]].<ref name="web.archive.org-2023" />
== Legacy == According to the Nihongi's account of [[Emperor Sujin]], Takehi-Nateru descended from heaven with divine treasures. These treasures were kept at [[Izumo-taisha]] and later handed over to the [[Emperor of Japan]]. However, this transfer led to conflicts among the Izumo, Furune, and Iiirine family branches, who were the keepers of these sacred items. Today, shrines in [[Izumo Province|Izumo]] and [[Inaba Province|Inaba]] honor Takehi-Nateru.<ref name="web.archive.org-2023" />
